en","1245–1347":"1245–1347","1262–1313":"1262–1313","Aft 1299":"na 1299","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1262":"1262","1347":"1347","1313":"1313","1345":"1345","1356":"1356","Abt 1277":"circa 1277","1245":"1245","1299":"1299","about 1299":"circa 1299","Of, Twyford,, England":"Twyford, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Grendon, Northamptonshire, England":"Grendon, Northamptonshire, England","Burton upon Trent St Mowden, Derbyshire, England":"Burton upon Trent St Modwen, Derbyshire, England"},"en":{"1275–Aft 1299":"1275–after 1299","1275–1299":"1275–1299","1285–1356":"1285–1356","1295–1345":"1295–1345","1299–Female":"1299–Deceased","1245–1347":"1245–1347","1262–1313":"1262–1313","Aft 1299":"after 1299","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1262":"1262","1347":"1347","1313":"1313","1345":"1345","1356":"1356","Abt 1277":"about 1277","1245":"1245","1299":"1299","about 1299":"about 1299","Of, Twyford,, England":"Twyford, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Grendon, Northamptonshire, England":"Grendon, Northamptonshire, England","Burton upon Trent St Mowden, Derbyshire, England":"Burton upon Trent St Modwen, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Twyford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places calledTwyford, for example in Berkshire, Buckinghamshire, Derbyshire,Hampshire, Leicestershire, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, and Norfolk, fromOld English <i>twī-</i> ‘double’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."],"variants":[{"name":"Twiford","meanings":["English: variant of   Twyford  ."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert de Twyford was born in 1275, his father, John de Twyford, was 30 and his mother, Margaret de Derbyshire, was 13. He married Mrs. Twyford about 1299, in Twyford, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died after 1299."},"et":{"1275–Aft 1299":"1275–pärast 1299","1275–1299":"1275–1299","1285–1356":"1285–1356","1295–1345":"1295–1345","1299–Female":"1299–Surnud","1245–1347":"1245–1347","1262–1313":"1262–1313","Aft 1299":"pärast 1299","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1262":"1262","1347":"1347","1313":"1313","1345":"1345","1356":"1356","Abt 1277":"umbes 1277","1245":"1245","1299":"1299","about 1299":"umbes 1299","Of, Twyford,, England":"Twyford, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Grendon, Northamptonshire, England":"Grendon, Northamptonshire, England","Burton upon Trent St Mowden, Derbyshire, England":"Burton upon Trent St Modwen, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"1275–Aft 1299":"1275–1299 jälkeen","1275–1299":"1275–1299","1285–1356":"1285–1356","1295–1345":"1295–1345","1299–Female":"1299–Kuollut","1245–1347":"1245–1347","1262–1313":"1262–1313","Aft 1299":"1299 jälkeen","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1262":"1262","1347":"1347","1313":"1313","1345":"1345","1356":"1356","Abt 1277":"noin 1277","1245":"1245","1299":"1299","about 1299":"noin 1